segments.text: We're talking about the fact that we're seeing high density in a traditional sense, high density, rather than the Houston notion of high density, 16 units to the acre.
We're talking about high rise condominiums.
We're seeing these things springing up in these activity centers that you would have normally, through a planning process, I would assume, put your residential areas

uh around those activity centers to minimize the travel and we're seeing that take place right now in greenway plaza around the downtown area continuing demand for residential properties around the the downtown area and around the greenway plaza galleria area well those are three no more there's probably more
It just depends on what you want.
You can call it Greenspoint Mall, Sharpstown Mall, Gulfgate, Northwest Crossing.
The big three basically are the Galleria, Greenway Plaza, and Downtown.
Medical Center is a little different kind of operation, but it's a big one too.
But I think that
Whether the market forces, you know, the market doesn't give a goddamn what happens.
The market merely is a reflection of what is.

And they say it's a market approach, but whatever it is, there seems to be a clear, in my mind, a little bit of a turnaround toward continued expansion, you know, lot after lot after lot, because it's just too goddamn expensive.
You know, you get the fuel costs, the heating and cooling costs.
It's becoming a little bit prohibitive, especially for young people, to buy a single family house, number one.
Number two, if they buy one, it's out 35 miles from the city, and they've got to pay to drive in and out of town.
That's a problem.
Of course, on the other hand, you've got some corporations moving out into the suburbs.
So we've got both, you know, you don't know whether the people follow the jobs or the jobs follow the people.
We've got both phenomena occurring right here.
On balance, do you think, which direction is being favored currently?
Is there a centripetal or a centripetal force?
Well, you can look around downtown and see what we've got going in.
Which is?
A lot of
very tall buildings, a lot of office space, like Texas Commerce Tower.
How many stories?
That was 75.
We've got a 70-story building that hadn't gotten out of the hole yet and just finished a 65-story, which is the first international plaza.
First city's built a couple of big buildings.
I'm not sure how big they are.
But that's the Gerald Hines building,
the one we're talking about across the city hall, the Ken Schnitzer building, that's a Gerald Pines building.
So you do have, you know, an intensification of downtown office space, and most of these places are new stuff now, even before the...
But you do have, you've got movement out to the suburbs as well.
Is it on, would you say...
the equal of the in-city development?
It probably is.
It's not as dramatic because you don't see it.
It doesn't go straight up.
But I don't know what the balance is.
I really don't.
Maybe Roscoe, as planner, would know that.
He probably does.
That's a good question for Roscoe.
Now, tell me about transportation.
in Houston since you've been here.
Where has it come from?
What are its problems?
And where withergoes Houston in terms of mass transportation?
And I suppose that in mass transportation, we ought to include mass transit as well as the freeway system, if you want to call it a freeway system, which to me is a misnomer in the case of Houston.
What do you mean?
It ain't free.
There ain't no way.
It's virtually always bottlenecked and quite hazardous.
I would say it's probably the poorest designed urban freeway system I have encountered in the United States.
Personally, as a planner, I would say that.
For you or Mayor McConnell.
Yeah, I think that they...
They didn't limit access enough on the dock is the main problem.
On the gulf?
Huh?
On the gulf?
No, on any of it.
On any of it?
On Southwest Freeway in particular inside the loop.
It's ridiculous.
You're getting on while somebody's getting off.
Sometimes you can't.
It is a mess.
And the signing seems to assume that you are a resident and have been since birth.
Yeah, yeah.
I'll buy that sometimes.
It's a little confusing.
And you never know where to turn until the moment of truth, and then it's too late.
It very well may be.
I don't know.
You've become used to it.
Yeah, I've talked to the highway department.
The highway boys, that's all they do.
If you're a stranger in town, it's merciless.
I think it's much better than Dallas.
Much easier to me.
That's no distraction.
Yeah, well, I mean, we're always being compared to Dallas, which is like comparing San Francisco to Los Angeles.
I mean, it's almost the same parallel.
I wouldn't want to do that.
No, I mean, but not comparing San Francisco to Dallas or L.A. to Houston, but the various mentalities.
People do compare Houston to Los Angeles, and in all candor, when I hear this said, I recoil.
This is not my interview, but I can't help but get into the actor a little bit, being from the West Coast and California, I know, as it were, to some degree.
But, you know, there are parts of Los Angeles that are downright beautiful.
Oh, yeah.
There are parts of Houston that are downright beautiful.
Well, you've got to look for them, and you've got to look very hard for them.
Whereas in Los Angeles, they're apparent.
and they are outrageously beautiful and attractive, and everything is done right from the planning point of view.
Now, I don't believe that Houston has any rightful claim to be the Los Angeles of Texas.
We don't mean to be.
We mean to be the Houston of Texas.
That's all.
Okay, you said it.
Yes, I did.
Now, what does this mean?
Nothing.
We have, in Houston, we have, I think of it as,
a very Texan mentality when it comes to governance.
And the people of this city do not like intervention on the part of the government.
And although you hear people bitching about the streets being bad and the garbage not being picked up and everything, there is a refusal
on the part of the powers that be to want to pay for a higher quality of service.
When push comes to shove, you can talk about efficiency and everything.
But when you're underfunded 400%, you're not going to be able to do your job.
And the cost of government goes up just like the cost of everything else.
And I think that people are willing to pass bond issues
And they're willing to pay, but they don't want to very much.
And I think the city, since I've been here, I think we're getting more.
Houston was considered a place where you worked and not where you lived.
And I think we're getting a little turnaround.
We're getting some people here to say, hey, you know, this is the shits.
You know, let's clean it up.
Let's do something about it.
And there's some people that are really trying to do that.
And there's some people that say, you know,
Forget it.
I'm not going to pay.
It's a place where you make a fast buck, and there are some people like that.
I don't think that that totally pervades the whole society like we are accused of in many places.
Especially as the popular press currently.
Popular press.
I get real sick of that crap, okay, because... Texas business... Well, fine, but they're Dallas outfits.
Okay.
I would find working in Dallas extremely boring unless I was in the tax office and I would have probably been fired like their tax assessor was on their evaluation.
To me, that's boring.
They are, for all practical purposes, they could consider themselves just like an eastern city.
They're surrounded by suburbs, suburban villages, towns.
They can't annex them.
We're not.
And we won't allow that to happen.
The downside of that is that
In terms of federal funding, we didn't talk about it at lunch, but I'd like to get at it.
We did manage to get the pockets of poverty provisions applied in the UDAG regulations.
Because you're really dealing, if you deal with Houston, you're dealing with a region almost.

And because the fact that we annex our suburbs and don't let them incorporate, nor are we going to start, by the way, we have an extremely high tax base, but we do have areas of the city that have been neglected for many, many years because of the fact that the continued growth drained the city coffers.
And now, basically, the new annexations are enabling us to renovate and
revitalized some of our inner city neighborhoods.
And clearly they're paying the bill.
So it's not the fault of the suburban areas.
We're annexing these areas and they're saying, well, fine, you know, and we don't have any parks.
But those guys out there are paying for the revitalization.
So the mistakes that were made were in the past and not particularly right now.
The last two administrations have had a very strong policy toward inner city revitalization.
If we've got
capital projects, for example, of equal merit, we're going to put those suckers inside the loop in the inner city.
And that's the policy.
I see on the map up here the Woodlands and Tomball, which, well, Tomball is within the county and Woodlands is not.

People are experiencing problems now who live in the woodlands of commuting into Houston, and I think that they're attempting to resolve these, not perhaps solve them, but resolve them in terms of carpooling and so forth.
Would you care to comment on the problem that Houston faces with
the impact of energy on places like the Woodlands, outlying communities that have a clear economic relationship to Houston itself?
Well, they've got a clear economic relationship, but it may not be a homework journey related.
A good many people in the woodlands work in the woodlands.
One of the things that Mental Energy had tried to do was to get a contained situation.
And there are a number of vanpools coming from the woodlands in the downtown.
And there's a number of employers, for example, that are using vanpools.
It's been very, very successful here.
They've really done well.
Utilization of contraflow lanes.
But there's
Again, I'm quoting a public works deputy director.
We're about 20 years behind in our surface transportation streets and maybe 30 in drainage because of the magnitude of the growth.
And the fact that in annexing outlying areas, we picked up a whole lot of crap, a whole lot of old county roads,
big crown, deep ditch.
And we're having to go in later and make those up to snuff.
And there's no real, again, one of the problems that you get with a non-zoning situation, the only way that we're controlling any kind of growth right now is by sewer permit.
And that's by court order.
And of course, that's not a very good way to control growth because waste load and waste flow doesn't necessarily mean anything.
Other than that, I'd hate to control growth from a sewer standpoint.
That's probably the last way I'd want to control it.
That's sort of the bottom end of the thing.
Yes, it is.
And the sewage doesn't care.
It is a problem.
Is it a policy of the city of Houston now to take a look at development directions in terms of whether or not they will grant a sewer permit for the area?
I'm sorry?
Right now, before you get a building permit, you have to get a letter of availability from the city.
So that can mean any number of things.
If a plant is overloaded, you don't get a permit.
If a collection line, interceptor source, whatever is overloaded, you don't get a permit.
But is it all mechanical like that?
Is it merely an engineering consideration, or is it a growth policy consideration?
By definition, it's a growth policy consideration, but it is an engineering reasoning.
In other words, if the pipes won't handle it, you don't get the permit.
I wouldn't call that planning by any stretch of the imagination.
It's not like if you put an apartment building down here, it's going to create so many cars that you'll never get up the street.
That's not considered.
What is considered is if those 160 units are going to overflow somewhere.
And then you don't get your permit.
And four-fifths of the city, I think, are restricted this time to five units to the acre.
Five units to the acre.
And that's at a time when we ought to be wide open in the inner city.
It's a shame.
Because now the market is such that a good number of areas could be redeveloped at a higher density.
And we can't do it because we'll all go to jail.
Because we've got a court order saying we've got to do this and we've got to do that.
Well, Mayor McCann was on television recently saying that they were spending X
millions of dollars to double the capacity of the sewage treatment facility in Houston.
Could you elaborate on that and also what the city expects to be able to do as a consequence?
OK. Well, over the next four years, the city plans to spend in total funding about $2.4 billion in physical facilities development.
We've got about $732 million of wastewater facilities planned.
That includes anticipated EPA funding and our revenue bonds.
We should, at the end of 1983, be able to handle our projected waste load.
on any growth option you choose.
The major problem in the city is the north side sewage treatment plant, which covers roughly the north half of the city.
And it was designed for about 50 MGD, and it was liable to run 75 or 100 on a wet day.
We've got a multi-million dollar
I think it's about 150 million and counting sister plant to that one, located on the bio around the loop.
When you say on a wet day, that causes me to wonder if the sewage system for Houston has been divided into storm sewers and domestic sewers.
Yes, it has been.
They're separate.
They're separate?
Yes.
I think the last combination sewer, I think, was downtown.
I think we did away with it.
What we do have is portions of the system that have just worn out.
And you do get your infiltration.
I see.
Okay, well, you're worlds ahead of San Francisco.
No, we don't do combined.
No, to treat stormwater runoff in the city of Houston, no, we couldn't afford it.
I mean, that's dumb.
We don't want to do that.
Anywhere.
No, no.
No way, Jose.
Uh-uh.
No, but we, you know, in our water system, the same way we're looking to spend roughly the same amount of money on the water system.
It needs to be reworked.
We have a loop system.
It's one system throughout the city.
And we're looking at improving it, a major rework of that system.
With EPA funds?
No, there's no EPA funds for water.
We do it on our rates.
And therefore, we're looking at increased water rates.
But people are having to pay now, I think, for the luxury that they were afforded 10 years ago.
I think that the bullet was beginning to be bitten with hawkins, and I think the mayor now has bitten even more of it.
But we've got to do it.
It's very unpleasant and politically very unpopular.
But somebody's got to pay the piper.
And the balloon notes do.
OK, well, Rick, there have been critics of architecture and of planning in the past who have noticed certain characteristics about Houston, which
they have commented upon in one way or another, usually with some negative thoughts.
Do you believe that the planning process exists in Houston?
Do you believe that it's effective?
Do you think that it's capable in terms of what we as planners
identify as a planning process to handle the challenges of the future in Houston?
Yeah, I think regardless of... What changes would you, you know, envision as being appropriate?
Well, one thing I have a problem with planning and planners about is that they don't want to be political.
That they are the
I don't remember which idiot wrote it, but saying they just merely make recommendations to the decision maker.
Well, to me, if you're not political, then you're not in the decision process.

So I would suggest, you know, somebody telling me they're not going to be political, I'm going to tell them to drop dead because I don't want to hear what they're saying because it's not going to matter.
So to me, planning, the worst thing that's happened to planning is that it got out of the politics.
Because the politics are what makes the decisions.

Whereas I think that some planning expertise interjected into the political process could be much better than sitting over there and all those weirdos over here talking about this shit that they don't know anything about.
We're going to do this because I got the money.
It's the golden rule.
I got the role.
The gold makes the rules.
I find that we do have a planning process here.
It's very political.
I think that more planning rules, planning theory, is being interjected into the decision process here, whereas before it wasn't.
I think people are more interested in planning considerations now rather than pure economic considerations than there were before.
And I see that happening for the virtue of me being appointed where I am.
Who wants a planter on their goddamn stand?
And so I feel that the planting profession itself has done itself an injustice by not being political, not getting in there and, you know, well, I recommended no.
Well, you know, that was ridiculous.
And so you're clean and free.
And I think too many planters cover their ass first without thinking for a minute why their ass is there in the first place.
And I think that's the major failing of planting.
And I think

in defense of the houston planning process you know there are a lot of planners around here that may not call themselves planners but to me planning for something without any insurance that it's going to occur is sort of a futile exercise and i think that that planning in a sense of houston without the zoning traditional land use management or controls or whatever
You know, I think we have a planning process.

It might be between me and the director of public works and the mayor and a couple of developers, but there is a process by which development occurs and regardless of how disorderly it may appear, we know it's happening.
You know, again, there has been an absence of planning regimens stuck into the decision process and I think that

it's turning around here roscoe may disagree with me but i i find that that's the case i find that's a major shortcoming of planners in general as they refuse to be political with the exception of maybe what's his name in san francisco no jacobs jacobs yeah jacobs kind of got in there yeah but most planning directors don't roy alcobar you know was removed unceremoniously a couple of weeks ago i didn't know that
Of course, he's an architect now, aside from that.
But could you briefly give us a kind of a thumbnail sketch of the planning process in Houston, aside from the generalities?
There's a planning department, and then, of course, your role here in the mayor's office, and then there's council and all that.
Well, I'm not real sure I understand what you're saying.
I'm not quite sure how to ask the question.
I'm trying to figure out what tool.
We're talking about physical facilities planning.
I think basically most people planning think of land use planning.
But an overall resource allocation, which I consider planning.
But for example, is there much opportunity for private citizens to be involved in the process?
Are there any citizens groups that are pressure groups, advocacy groups in Houston?
Do they have any effect on the overall process of community development at all?
In terms of the, it just depends on the myriad of programs we have.
In community development, for example, City Museum, they have a direct input.
I mean, they get to pick what they want, basically, unless it runs uphill or something.
The city, by and large, does that.
For a while, Houston had mobile city halls in the neighborhood, as I remember, under the model cities program.
Yes, we did.
when the citizens could go into their own neighborhood city hall and they wouldn't feel so intimidated about appearing in a municipal edifice.
They would happen to be a trader in their neighborhood park, whereas they might feel somewhat more apprehensive about coming to city hall and attending a city council meeting.
Well, of course, the thing that the Model City program did
throughout the country, I think, was show the people the way to city hall.
It did so here.
And we have numerous citizens appearing before the city council as well as getting calls all day about complaints.
We don't have as active an inspection and keeping our own house because of just the sheer
570 square miles of the city because people ride around trying to find things wrong.
We barely can do that.
The city has gotten much more responsive, I think, with the new council since we switched from an at-large to a district council at answering citizen complaints.
But it's basically up to the citizen to say, hey, my street's messed up or
hey, my water line's broken because we just don't have the resources to do that.
We barely have enough resources to get things fixed.
But I mean, it's not like it's just spread out.
I mean, the physical, the geographical makeup of the city is such that it's really very difficult to do proper maintenance.
Another question I have is, in view of the fact that Houston has this incredible economy, how is it that the city can't take care of its day-to-day needs and just keep things patched up and so forth?
I mean, a lot of communities I can think of offhand would be delighted to have some of the industrial base that Houston has as revenue potential.
Is there some problem with the revenue aspect of this?
No, it may be a matter of whether or not the city council will agree to tax the citizenry at a rate required to hire the people and provide the material.
When you say the citizenry, do you mean residences?
I'm talking about the ad valorem tax, which is the large share of our...
OK.
Applied to industrial plants as well.
Just the fact that the taxes that we're bringing in are insufficient in most people's minds to do the job.
Last year, for example, the mayor proposed a 10 cent tax increase for street maintenance, which would raise, I don't know what it is, 1,600,000 per penny
in a millage, and the council turning down.
We are in a tax freeze with 77 values, and this year we're in deep trouble because of inflation, frozen tax values, and an election year.
So they're not about to raise taxes in an election year.
So we're really in trouble this year, and it's a bad time for anybody
than to be running for office right now because there's just not enough money.
We ran out of money to pick up the garbage last year.
We've run out of money, and we're just not really responsive to the needs of the city government.
It's like, well, we've got to save money.
Time to retrench and tread water a bit.
Yeah, yeah.
That's sort of what it is, increased verbosity.

Now the other two points that I wanted to mention is one in terms of transportation planning in the city of Houston that I don't feel personally as a planner that the transit solution, be it a myriad of buses, heavy rail system,
or whatever in itself is going to solve our problems in the city of Houston.
I think that basically it's a land use solution, and some controls need to be applied to ensure the success of the system and that the system works.
Because you just can't superimpose a grid on 570 square miles of the city and expect everybody to be able to go where they need to go.
